## Notes and Additional Considerations from r1 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r1 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### Two strangers

The simplest crowd is two. Each moves on its own clock, but each *sees* the other.

```scheme
(motion
  (define (stranger-a)
    (sprite
      (shape 'circle 20)
      (color 0.2 0.5 0.8 1.0)
      (route
        (to (xy 100 200) 2.0 'ease-out)
        (wait 0.5)
        (to (xy 300 200) 2.0 'ease-in-out))))
  
  (define (stranger-b)
    (sprite
      (shape 'circle 20)
      (color 0.8 0.3 0.2 1.0)
      (route
        (to (xy 300 200) 1.8 'ease-out)
        (wait 0.3)
        (to (xy 100 200) 1.8 'ease-in-out))))
  
  (world
    (spawn (stranger-a))
    (spawn (stranger-b))))
```

[VISUAL: Two circles crossing paths, each on its own trajectory, never acknowledging the other.]

They pass like ships. Now let them pause when close:

```scheme
(motion
  (define (aware-a)
    (sprite
      (shape 'circle 18)
      (color 0.3 0.6 0.7 1.0)
      (route
        (to (xy 150 250) 1.5 'ease-out)
        (wait 1.0)
        (to (xy 350 250) 2.0 'ease-in))))
  
  (define (aware-b)
    (sprite
      (shape 'circle 18)
      (color 0.7 0.4 0.3 1.0)
      (route
        (to (xy 350 250) 1.5 'ease-out)
        (wait 0.8)
        (to (xy 150 250) 2.0 'ease-in))))
  
  (world
    (spawn (aware-a))
    (spawn (aware-b))))
```

[VISUAL: Two circles approach, linger near the center, then continue. The timing creates a moment of proximity.]

Timing alone can suggest awareness. The wait durations create a \"near miss\" that reads as hesitation.

---


### A line of three

Queues are crowds in one dimension. Each entity maintains spacing from the one ahead.

```scheme
(motion
  (define (person idx total)
    (sprite
      (shape 'circle 16)
      (color 0.4 0.5 0.6 1.0)
      (route
        (let ((start-x (+ 50 (* idx 80)))
              (target-x (+ 450 (* idx 80))))
          (from (xy start-x 300))
          (to (xy target-x 300) 3.0 'ease-in-out)))))
  
  (world
    (spawn (person 0 3))
    (spawn (person 1 3))
    (spawn (person 2 3))))
```

[VISUAL: Three circles moving right in formation, evenly spaced.]

Same target, staggered starts:

```scheme
(motion
  (define (staggered-person idx)
    (sprite
      (shape 'circle 14)
      (color 0.5 0.6 0.4 1.0)
      (route
        (wait (* idx 0.4))
        (to (xy 400 280) 2.5 'ease-out))))
  
  (world
    (spawn (staggered-person 0))
    (spawn (staggered-person 1))
    (spawn (staggered-person 2))
    (spawn (staggered-person 3))))
```

[VISUAL: Four circles launching in sequence like a wave, all converging on the same point.]

---


### The grid wake-up

A grid of sleepers, each waking on a slightly offset clock.

```scheme
(motion
  (define (sleeper row col)
    (sprite
      (shape 'circle 12)
      (color 0.3 0.3 0.4 1.0)
      (route
        (let ((x (+ 100 (* col 60)))
              (y (+ 100 (* row 60)))
              (delay (* (+ row col) 0.15)))
          (from (xy x y))
          (wait delay)
          (scale 1.0)
          (to-scale 1.5 0.3 'ease-out)
          (to-scale 1.0 0.3 'ease-in)))))
  
  (world
    (spawn (sleeper 0 0))
    (spawn (sleeper 0 1))
    (spawn (sleeper 0 2))
    (spawn (sleeper 1 0))
    (spawn (sleeper 1 1))
    (spawn (sleeper 1 2))
    (spawn (sleeper 2 0))
    (spawn (sleeper 2 1))
    (spawn (sleeper 2 2))))
```

[VISUAL: A 3×3 grid of circles, each pulsing slightly larger and back in a diagonal wave from top-left to bottom-right.]

The delay formula `(* (+ row col) 0.15)` creates a diagonal sweep.

